ceasn:description.en-us: Associate Safety Professionals (ASP) are persons who performs at least 50% of professional level safety duties including; are making worksite assessments to determine risks, potential hazards and controls, evaluating risks and hazard control measures, investigating incidents, maintaining and evaluating incident and loss records, and preparing emergency response plans. Other duties could include; hazard recognition, fire protection, regulatory compliance, health hazard control, ergonomics, hazardous materials management, environmental protection, training, accident and incident, investigations, advising management, record keeping, emergency response, managing safety programs, product safety and/or security.

ceasn:competencyText.en-us: Sources (e.g., assessment, control strategies, symptoms, target organs)
Environmental hazards awareness (e.g., biological [mold], chemical, waste, vermin)
Data collection, needs analysis, and feedback
Selection of control methods (e.g., financial justification, hierarchy of controls)
Risk analysis methods (e.g., job safety analysis, hazard and operability analysis, failure mode and effects analysis, fault tree analysis, fishbone, what-if and checklist analysis, change analysis)
Climate conditions (e.g., WBGT, wind chill, heat stress)
Material handling (e.g. manual, powered equipment, lifting devices)
Work practice controls (e.g., job rotation, work hardening)
Fire Science (e.g., combustible dust fire pentagon, fire triangle, fire tetrahedron)
Qualitative methods (e.g., Rapid Upper Limb Assessment [RULA], Rapid Whole Body Assessment [REBA])
Quantitative methods (e.g., anthropometry, NIOSH lift equation)
Driver behavior (e.g., defensive driving, distracted driving)
Written plans, procedures, and work practices (e.g., Incident Command system, fire brigade)
Land and conservation (e.g., solid waste, recycling, sustainability)
Lagging indicators (e.g., incidence rates, lost time, direct costs of incidents)
Hazard Communication and Globally Harmonized System
Evaluation of cost, schedule, performance, and risk
Exposure limits (e.g., PELs, TLVs, STELs, RELs)
Presentation tools (e.g., computer based, group meeting)
Segregation and separation (e.g., flammable materials storage, ventilation)
Emergency, crisis, disaster response planning, business continuity
Safety features (e.g., restraint systems, automatic and anti-lock braking systems)
Substitution and selection of alternative design strategies
Cost benefit analysis (e.g., cost of risk)
Routes of entry (e.g., inhalation, ingestion, absorption, injection)
Correlational statistics (e.g., Pearson's r, Spearman's rho)
Risk Management and Hazard Control Process
Above ground (AST) and underground (UST) storage tanks
Risk factors (e.g., repetition, force, posture, vibration)
Written plans, procedures, work practices (e.g., decontamination)

Leading indicators (e.g., inspection frequency, safety interventions, employee performance evaluations, training frequency,
near miss, near hit, and close call reporting)
